Time: O(n)
Space: O(h)

# Definition for a binary tree node.
# class TreeNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.left = left
#         self.right = right
class Solution:
    def lcaDeepestLeaves(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> Optional[TreeNode]:
        def dfs(node):
            if node is None:
                return 0, None
            
            left_depth, left_lca = dfs(node.left)
            right_depth, right_lca = dfs(node.right)

            if left_depth > right_depth:
                return left_depth + 1, left_lca

            if right_depth > left_depth:
                return right_depth + 1, right_lca
            
            return left_depth + 1, node

        return dfs(root)[1]



- Why this works
At every node, compare the maximum leaf depth in the left and right subtrees.

Left side is deeper
if left_depth > right_depth:
    return left_depth + 1, left_lca

All deepest leaves are in the left subtree, so the answer must also be inside the left subtree.

Right side is deeper
if right_depth > left_depth:
    return right_depth + 1, right_lca

All deepest leaves are in the right subtree.

Both sides have the same depth
return left_depth + 1, node

This means the deepest leaves exist on both sides.

Therefore, the current node is the lowest node containing all of them, so it is their LCA.

Example

Consider:

        1
       / \
      2   3
     / \
    4   5

The deepest leaves are 4 and 5.

